      "text": "Keys to Resilient Supply Chains 2 Supply chain disruptions are becoming the new normal. Conflicts, wars, extreme weather events leading to natural disasters, ongoing geopolitical tensions, regulatory uncertainty and economic fluctuations and threats of cyber-attacks have highlighted the importance of boosting resilience. Increased pressure on the logistics and transport industry coupled with frequent congestion, labour and container shortages and rising prices have put additional strain on supply chains. The persistence of these events increases pressure on companies, but also on governments to anticipate, respond and recover from acute external shocks. Supply chain resilience can therefore be defined as the ability of a supply chain to return to normal operations following a disruption. Governments are increasingly expected to play a significant role not only in ensuring the resilience of critical supply chains, but also in co-ordinating with the private sector to respond to similar",
